SIMPLE: junior
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Junior
<hw>Jun"ior</hw> <pr>(j⟦umac⟧n"y⟦etil⟧r; 277)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos>
<ety>[L. contr. fr. <ets>juvenior</ets>, compar. of <ets>juvenis</ets>
young. See <er>Juvenile</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Less advanced in age than another; younger.
Abbreviated <abbr>Jr.</abbr></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Junior</xex> is applied to distinguish the younger
of two persons bearing the same name in the same family, and is opposed
to <contr>senior or elder</contr>. Commonly applied to a son who has the
same Christian name as his father.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Lower in standing or in rank, or having entered
later into a position or office; <as>as, a <ex>junior</ex> partner;
<ex>junior</ex> counsel; <ex>junior</ex> captain; the <ex>junior</ex>
Senator from New York.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Composed of juniors, whether younger or a lower
standing; <as>as, the <ex>junior</ex> class; the <ex>junior</ex>
baseball league</as>; of or pertaining to juniors or to a junior class.
See <er>Junior</er>, <pos>n.</pos>, 2.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Belonging to a younger person, or an earlier time of
life.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Our first studies and <qex>junior</qex> endeavors.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir T. Browne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>of or relating to the third year of a four-year
term; -- used of the third or next to final year in a U. S. high school
or college. See <er>junior</er>{2}, <pos>n.</pos>.</def>⟦br⟧
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> third-year.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Junior</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Junior
<hw>Jun"ior</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A younger
person.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His <qex>junior</qex> she, by thirty years.</q>
<rj><qau>Byron.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <specif>Hence:</specif> <def>One of a lower or later
standing; specifically, in American colleges and four-year high schools,
one in the third year of his course, one in the fourth or final year
being designated a <contr>senior</contr>; in some seminaries, one in the
first year, in others, one in the second year, of a three years'
course.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Juniority</ent>⟦br⟧
